The main idea for fluid flow simulation is the incompressible Navier-Stokes equations. The equations are ∂⃗u/∂t + u  · ∇⃗u + 1/ρ ∇p = g  + ν∇ · ∇⃗u and ∇ · u  = 0.

u is the velocity of the fluid. The greek letter ρ is for the density. The normal p is for pressure, which is the force per unit area that the fluid exerts on anything. g is just gravity, as well as any additional control accelerations that might be wanted on top of gravity. These are also called body forces. The Greek letter ν is the kinematic viscosity. The first equation is the momentum equation, and really is just F = ma. The second one is the incompressibility condition.

	We need to find the net forces acting on a particle. To do that we find the negative gradient of pressure, -∇⃗p and multiply by volume V. The other fluid force is due to viscosity, which is a force that makes a particle move at the same speed as the nearby particles. We can use the Laplacian, which is a differential operator that measures how far a quantity is from the average around it. Using that and integrating over the volume, as well as the dynamic viscosity coefficient, μ. Then the F = ma equation becomes m D⃗ u/Dt = m⃗ g − V ∇p + V μ∇ · ∇⃗u. This is just for individual particles, so we take the limit as the number of particles goes to infinity  and the size goes to zero. First we divide by V so we get something meaningful, and m/V = density, ρ. Taking the limit and rearranging you get D⃗ uDt + (1/ρ) ∇p =⃗ g + (μ/ρ) ∇ · ∇⃗u.We replace μ/ρ as viscosity, ν, and get D⃗ u/Dt + (1/ρ) ∇p =⃗ g + ν∇ · ∇⃗u

	It is easy to think of D⃗ u/Dt as a point in space, and ask how much the quantity is changing for the particle who is at a position as a function of time. You use the chain rule, and the first term is how fast the quantity is changing at a fixed point in space, and the second term is correctoring for how much of that change is just due to differences in the fluid flowing past. This means that even when the Lagrangian derivative is zero, the Eulerian derivative can be anything, depending on the velocity of the fluid.

	Another key idea is that fluids are incompressible (pretty much). We measure how fast the volume is changing by integrating the normal component of its velocity around the boundary. d/dt volume(Ω) =∫ ∫∂Ω⃗ u · ˆn, and because it’s incompressible, the change in volume = 0. Using the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, you get ∫ ∫ ∫Ω∇ ·⃗ u = 0, and so ∇ ·⃗ u = 0.
